>Not so much Aware Truman Show as a bunch of "experts" speculating as to what sort of abuses he was subjected to
That sounds better but I stand by my first take: This is a development, not a plot.
There's a lot of farcical humor beats in the "oblivious but proud scientists making huge mistakes" line, via dramatic irony since we readers know that these are gaffs and will expect that later they will pay off with the scientists either tangling themselves in contradictory assertions and probably arguing about them or humbling themselves when the truth is revealed and they're shown to have egg on their faces. But that's a B-plot, that's comedy relief, that's a story beat.
The premise needs to address the conflict. If Isekai Boy is just pretending to be retarded to get through the day, then he needs to have a plan or goal for later.
Some tried and true tropes for this:
>He finds a way back and must navigate to that goal without blowing his tard cover
>He finds someone he wants to trust and must test that person's trustworthiness and find a way for both of them to extract from this circumstance together
>He finds others also playing possum and must either join their charade or risk being exposed by their combined effort
>He finds there is something else going on that caused his Isekai event that becomes his hero's journey call to action
>It's all a dream of a comatose guy who was a TV actor playing a man pretending to be an amnesiac in an isekai world! What a twist!
Anyway, unless you go full farce your 2nd story only lives as long as the same joke can stay amusing by being told in different ways. We know from Fraiser that if you're a really good comedy writer, you can pull off about 22 minutes plus commercial breaks and by that point it's getting stretched REALLY thin. If you're going beyond a short piece, you need some sort of quality plot and story, too. And then, don't forget that Mel Brooks wrote about 6+ hours of material to get a 2 hour film to be funny.

Holy shit, it looks like someone is trying to use greentext format for anything that isn't a speculative second person drabble. And why the fuck is the establishment in the penultimate line?

Content wise, you're playing the most fundamental form of this trope. The problem is that comedy got beyond this in the vaudeville era. You're playing the "Say goodnight, Gracie" bit that was a one liner back then and came back as a stale sensible chuckle in the era of Warner Brothers animation both classical (~1950's) and revival (~1990's), but didn't hold up for more than one turn of conversation.

You need to evolve this so it's not just the same line appearing twice again and again. In particular this is because this kind of gag doesn't actually work well in text. You're relying on differences as slight as the presence or absence of a comma to hold all of the humor which is in linguistic inflection and body language (both are things text fails at) so if the reader doesn't correctly guess that in his imagination (i.e. be one of the few people who hasn't already seen this gag) it won't work at all. That puts you in the awkward position of having a scene that can only be either confusing or stale, depending on if the reader "gets it."

Another weakness is that your target character has no character. Now, there actually is a way to leverage that, but you didn't because you don't have your head in the action of the scene. The scene is trying to come alive but you're still working the formula from the first passages.

It's Sunday, I'll give it a once over.
